# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: expander-graphs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The **algebraic connectivity** (also known as **Fiedler value** or **Fiedler eigenvalue** after Miroslav Fiedler) of a graph *G* is the second-smallest eigenvalue (counting multiple eigenvalues separately) of the Laplacian matrix of *G*.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] This eigenvalue is greater than 0 if and only if *G* is a connected graph.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] This is a corollary to the fact that the number of times 0 appears as an eigenvalue in the Laplacian is the number of connected components in the graph.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The magnitude of this value reflects how well connected the overall graph is.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] It has been used in analyzing the robustness and synchronizability of networks.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The algebraic connectivity of undirected graphs with nonnegative weights is $a(G)\geq 0$ , with the inequality being strict if and only if G is connected.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] However, the algebraic connectivity can be negative for general directed graphs, even if *G* is a connected graph.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] Furthermore, the value of the algebraic connectivity is bounded above by the traditional (vertex) connectivity of a graph, ${\text{algebraic connectivity}}\leq {\text{connectivity}}$ , unless the graph is complete (the algebraic connectivity of a complete graph Kn is its order n).
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] For an undirected connected graph with nonnegative edge weights, *n* vertices, and diameter *D*, the algebraic connectivity is also known to be bounded below by ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{nD}}}$ , and in fact (in a result due to Brendan McKay) by ${\textstyle {\frac {4}{nD}}}$ .
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] In random graphs, the algebraic connectivity decreases with the number of vertices, and increases with the average degree.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The exact definition of the algebraic connectivity depends on the type of Laplacian used.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] Fan Chung has developed an extensive theory using a rescaled version of the Laplacian, eliminating the dependence on the number of vertices, so that the bounds are somewhat different.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] In models of synchronization on networks, such as the Kuramoto model, the Laplacian matrix arises naturally, so the algebraic connectivity gives an indication of how easily the network will synchronize.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] Other measures, such as the average distance (characteristic path length) can also be used, and in fact the algebraic connectivity is closely related to the (reciprocal of the) average distance.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The algebraic connectivity also relates to other connectivity attributes, such as the isoperimetric number, which is bounded below by half the algebraic connectivity.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The original theory related to algebraic connectivity was produced by Miroslav Fiedler.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] In his honor the eigenvector associated with the algebraic connectivity has been named the **Fiedler vector**.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The Fiedler vector can be used to partition a graph.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The negative values are associated with the poorly connected vertex 6, and the neighbouring articulation point, vertex 4; while the positive values are associated with the other vertices.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The signs of the values in the Fiedler vector can therefore be used to partition this graph into two components: ${\textstyle \{1,2,3,5\},\{4,6\}}$ .
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] Alternatively, the value of 0.069 (which is close to zero) can be placed in a class of its own, partitioning the graph into three components: ${\textstyle \{1,2,5\},\{3\},\{4,6\}}$ or moved to the other partition ${\textstyle \{1,2,5\},\{3,4,6\}}$ , as pictured.
[src:expander-graphs/algebraic-connectivity] The squared values of the components of the Fiedler vector, summing up to one since the vector is normalized, can be interpreted as probabilities of the corresponding data points to be assigned to the sign-based partition.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] In mathematics, the **Cheeger constant** (also **Cheeger number** or **isoperimetric number**) of a graph is a numerical measure of whether or not a graph has a "bottleneck".
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The Cheeger constant as a measure of "bottleneckedness" is of great interest in many areas: for example, constructing well-connected networks of computers, card shuffling.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The graph theoretical notion originated after the Cheeger isoperimetric constant of a compact Riemannian manifold.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The Cheeger constant is named after the mathematician Jeff Cheeger.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] Let G be an undirected finite graph with vertex set *V*(*G*) and edge set *E*(*G*).
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The Cheeger constant is strictly positive if and only if G is a connected graph.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] Intuitively, if the Cheeger constant is small but positive, then there exists a "bottleneck", in the sense that there are two "large" sets of vertices with "few" links (edges) between them.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The Cheeger constant is "large" if any possible division of the vertex set into two subsets has "many" links between those two subsets.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] In applications to theoretical computer science, one wishes to devise network configurations for which the Cheeger constant is high (at least, bounded away from zero) even when |*V*(*G*)| (the number of computers in the network) is large.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] For example, consider a ring network of *N* ≥ 3 computers, thought of as a graph GN.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] Number the computers 1, 2, ..., *N* clockwise around the ring.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] This example provides an upper bound for the Cheeger constant *h*(*GN*), which also tends to zero as *N* → ∞.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] Consequently, we would regard a ring network as highly "bottlenecked" for large N, and this is highly undesirable in practical terms.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] We would only need one of the computers on the ring to fail, and network performance would be greatly reduced.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] If two non-adjacent computers were to fail, the network would split into two disconnected components.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The Cheeger constant is especially important in the context of expander graphs as it is a way to measure the edge expansion of a graph.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The so-called Cheeger inequalities relate the eigenvalue gap of a graph with its Cheeger constant.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] in which $\Delta (G)$ is the maximum degree for the nodes in G and $\lambda$ is the spectral gap of the Laplacian matrix of the graph.
[src:expander-graphs/cheeger-constant-graph-theory] The Cheeger inequality is a fundamental result and motivation for spectral graph theory.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In graph theory, an **expander graph** is a sparse graph that has strong connectivity properties, quantified using vertex, edge or spectral expansion.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Expander constructions have spawned research in pure and applied mathematics, with several applications to complexity theory, design of robust computer networks, and the theory of error-correcting codes.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Intuitively, an expander graph is a finite, undirected multigraph in which every subset of the vertices that is not "too large" has a "large" boundary.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Different formalisations of these notions give rise to different notions of expanders: *edge expanders*, *vertex expanders*, and *spectral expanders*, as defined below.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] A disconnected graph is not an expander, since the boundary of a connected component is empty.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Every connected finite graph is an expander; however, different connected graphs have different expansion parameters.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The complete graph has the best expansion property, but it has largest possible degree.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Informally, a graph is a good expander if it has low degree and high expansion parameters.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] the edges between the subsets of vertices *A*,*B* ⊆ *V*(*G*).
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In the equation, the minimum is over all nonempty sets S of at most *n*⁄2 vertices and ∂*S* is the *edge boundary* of S, i.e., the set of edges with exactly one endpoint in S.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] is the minimum number of edges that need to be cut in order to split the graph in two.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The edge expansion normalizes this concept by dividing with smallest number of vertices among the two parts.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] To see how the normalization can drastically change the value, consider the following example.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Take two complete graphs with the same number of vertices n and add n edges between the two graphs by connecting their vertices one-to-one.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The minimum cut will be n but the edge expansion will be 1.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Notice that in min |∂*S*|, the optimization can be equivalently done either over 0 ≤ |*S*| ≤ *n*⁄2 or over any non-empty subset, since $E(S,{\overline {S}})=E({\overline {S}},S)$ .
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The same is not true for *h*(*G*) because of the normalization by |*S*|.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] where ∂out(*S*) is the *outer boundary* of S, i.e., the set of vertices in *V*(*G*) \ *S* with at least one neighbor in S.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In a variant of this definition (called *unique neighbor expansion*) ∂out(*S*) is replaced by the set of vertices in V with *exactly* one neighbor in S.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] where $\partial _{\text{in}}(S)$ is the *inner boundary* of S, i.e., the set of vertices in S with at least one neighbor in *V*(*G*) \ *S*.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] When G is d-regular, a linear algebraic definition of expansion is possible based on the eigenvalues of the adjacency matrix *A* = *A*(*G*) of G, where Aij is the number of edges between vertices i and j.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Because A is symmetric, the spectral theorem implies that A has n real-valued eigenvalues *λ*1 ≥ *λ*2 ≥ … ≥ *λ**n*.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] It is known that all these eigenvalues are in [−*d*, *d*] and more specifically, it is known that *λ**n* = −*d* if and only if G is bipartite.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The bound given by an (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graph on *λ**i* for *i* ≠ 1 is useful in many contexts, including the expander mixing lemma.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Spectral expansion can be *two-sided*, as above, with $\max _{i\neq 1}|\lambda _{i}|\leq \lambda$ , or it can be *one-sided*, with $\max _{i\neq 1}\lambda _{i}\leq \lambda$ .
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The latter is a weaker notion that holds also for bipartite graphs and is still useful for many applications, such as the Alon–Chung lemma.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Because G is regular, the uniform distribution $u\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with *ui* = 1⁄*n* for all *i* = 1, …, *n* is the stationary distribution of G.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] That is, we have *Au* = *du*, and u is an eigenvector of A with eigenvalue *λ*1 = *d*, where d is the degree of the vertices of G.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The *spectral gap* of G is defined to be *d* − *λ*2, and it measures the spectral expansion of the graph G.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] is the 2-norm of the vector $v\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The normalized versions of these definitions are also widely used and more convenient in stating some results.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Here one considers the matrix ⁠1/*d*⁠*A*, which is the Markov transition matrix of the graph G.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] For not necessarily regular graphs, the spectrum of a graph can be defined similarly using the eigenvalues of the Laplacian matrix.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] For directed graphs, one considers the singular values of the adjacency matrix A, which are equal to the roots of the eigenvalues of the symmetric matrix *A*T*A*.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] A family $(G_{i})_{i\in \mathbb {N} }$ of d -regular graphs of increasing size is an **expander family** if $h(G_{i})$ is bounded away from zero.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The expansion parameters defined above are related to each other.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Consequently, for constant degree graphs, vertex and edge expansion are qualitatively the same.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] When G is d-regular, meaning each vertex is of degree d, there is a relationship between the isoperimetric constant *h*(*G*) and the gap *d* − *λ*2 in the spectrum of the adjacency operator of G.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] By standard spectral graph theory, the trivial eigenvalue of the adjacency operator of a d-regular graph is *λ*1 = *d* and the first non-trivial eigenvalue is *λ*2.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The lower bound is achieved in limit for the hypercube Qn, where *h*(*G*) = 1 and *d* – *λ*2 = 2.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] These inequalities are closely related to the Cheeger bound for Markov chains and can be seen as a discrete version of Cheeger's inequality in Riemannian geometry.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Asymptotically speaking, the quantities *h*2⁄*d*, *h*out, and *h*in2 are all bounded above by the spectral gap *O*(*d* – *λ*2).
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] There are four general strategies for explicitly constructing families of expander graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The first strategy is algebraic and group-theoretic, the second strategy is analytic and uses additive combinatorics, the third strategy is combinatorial and uses the zig-zag and related graph products, and the fourth strategy is based on lifts.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Noga Alon showed that certain graphs constructed from finite geometries are the sparsest examples of highly expanding graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Algebraic constructions based on Cayley graphs are known for various variants of expander graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The following construction is due to Margulis and has been analysed by Gabber and Galil.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] By a theorem of Alon and Boppana, all sufficiently large d-regular graphs satisfy $\lambda _{2}\geq 2{\sqrt {d-1}}-o(1)$ , where *λ*2 is the second largest eigenvalue in absolute value.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] As a direct consequence, we know that for every fixed d and $\lambda <2{\sqrt {d-1}}$ , there are only finitely many (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Hence Ramanujan graphs have an asymptotically smallest possible value of *λ*2.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] This makes them excellent spectral expanders.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Lubotzky, Phillips, and Sarnak (1988), Margulis (1988), and Morgenstern (1994) show how Ramanujan graphs can be constructed explicitly.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In 1985, Alon, conjectured that most d-regular graphs on n vertices, for sufficiently large n, are almost Ramanujan.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] A simpler proof of a slightly weaker result was given by Puder.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Marcus, Spielman and Srivastava, gave a construction of bipartite Ramanujan graphs based on lifts.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Reingold, Vadhan, and Wigderson introduced the zig-zag product in 2000.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Roughly speaking, the zig-zag product of two expander graphs produces a graph with only slightly worse expansion.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Therefore, a zig-zag product can also be used to construct families of expander graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Note that property (1) implies that the zig-zag product of two expander graphs is also an expander graph, thus zig-zag products can be used inductively to create a family of expander graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Intuitively, the construction of the zig-zag product can be thought of in the following way.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Each vertex of G is blown up to a "cloud" of m vertices, each associated to a different edge connected to the vertex.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Each vertex is now labeled as (*v*, *k*) where v refers to an original vertex of G and k refers to the kth edge of v.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Two vertices, (*v*, *k*) and (*w*,*ℓ*) are connected if it is possible to get from (*v*, *k*) to (*w*, *ℓ*) through the following sequence of moves.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Jump across clouds using edge k' in G to get to (*w*, *ℓ′*).
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] An r-lift of a graph is formed by replacing each vertex by r vertices, and each edge by a matching between the corresponding sets of r vertices.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The lifted graph inherits the eigenvalues of the original graph, and has some additional eigenvalues.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Bilu and Linial showed that every d-regular graph has a 2-lift in which the additional eigenvalues are at most $O({\sqrt {d\log ^{3}d}})$ in magnitude.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] They also showed that if the starting graph is a good enough expander, then a good 2-lift can be found in polynomial time, thus giving an efficient construction of d-regular expanders for every d.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Bilu and Linial conjectured that the bound $O({\sqrt {d\log ^{3}d}})$ can be improved to $2{\sqrt {d-1}}$ , which would be optimal due to the Alon–Boppana bound.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] This conjecture was proved in the bipartite setting by Marcus, Spielman and Srivastava, who used the method of interlacing polynomials.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] As a result, they obtained an alternative construction of bipartite Ramanujan graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The original non-constructive proof was turned into an algorithm by Michael B.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Later the method was generalized to r-lifts by Hall, Puder and Sawin.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] There are many results that show the existence of graphs with good expansion properties through probabilistic arguments.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In fact, the existence of expanders was first proved by Pinsker who showed that for a randomly chosen n vertex left d regular bipartite graph, |*N*(*S*)| ≥ (*d* – 2)|*S*| for all subsets of vertices |*S*| ≤ *cdn* with high probability, where cd is a constant depending on d that is *O*(*d*-4).
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Alon and Roichman showed that for every 1 > *ε* > 0, there is some *c*(*ε*) > 0 such that the following holds: For a group G of order n, consider the Cayley graph on G with *c*(*ε*) log2 *n* randomly chosen elements from G.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Then, in the limit of n getting to infinity, the resulting graph is almost surely an *ε*-expander.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In 2021, Alexander modified an MCMC algorithm to look for randomized constructions to produce Ramanujan graphs with a fixed vertex size and degree of regularity.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The results show the Ramanujan graphs exist for every vertex size and degree pair up to 2000 vertices.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In 2024 Alon produced an explicit construction for near Ramanujan graphs of every vertex size and degree pair.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The original motivation for expanders is to build economical robust networks (phone or computer): an expander with bounded degree is precisely an asymptotic robust graph with the number of edges growing linearly with size (number of vertices), for all subsets.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Expander graphs have found extensive applications in computer science, in designing algorithms, error correcting codes, extractors, pseudorandom generators, sorting networks (Ajtai, Komlós & Szemerédi (1983)) and robust computer networks.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] They have also been used in proofs of many important results in computational complexity theory, such as SL = L (Reingold (2008)) and the PCP theorem (Dinur (2007)).
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In cryptography, expander graphs are used to construct hash functions.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In a 2006 survey of expander graphs, Hoory, Linial, and Wigderson split the study of expander graphs into four categories: extremal problems, typical behavior, explicit constructions, and algorithms.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Extremal problems focus on the bounding of expansion parameters, while typical behavior problems characterize how the expansion parameters are distributed over random graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Explicit constructions focus on constructing graphs that optimize certain parameters, and algorithmic questions study the evaluation and estimation of parameters.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The expander mixing lemma states that for an (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graph, for any two subsets of the vertices *S*, *T* ⊆ *V*, the number of edges between S and T is approximately what you would expect in a random d-regular graph.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The approximation is better the smaller *λ* is.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] In a random d-regular graph, as well as in an Erdős–Rényi random graph with edge probability *d*⁄*n*, we expect *d*⁄*n* • |*S*| • |*T*| edges between S and T.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] More formally, let *E*(*S*, *T*) denote the number of edges between S and T.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Many properties of (*n*, *d*, *λ*)-graphs are corollaries of the expander mixing lemmas, including the following.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The Chernoff bound states that, when sampling many independent samples from a random variable in the range [−1, 1], with high probability the average of our samples is close to the expectation of the random variable.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The expander walk sampling lemma, due to Ajtai, Komlós & Szemerédi (1987) and Gillman (1998), states that this also holds true when sampling from a walk on an expander graph.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] This is particularly useful in the theory of derandomization, since sampling according to an expander walk uses many fewer random bits than sampling independently.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Sorting networks take a set of inputs and perform a series of parallel steps to sort the inputs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] A parallel step consists of performing any number of disjoint comparisons and potentially swapping pairs of compared inputs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The depth of a network is given by the number of parallel steps it takes.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Expander graphs play an important role in the AKS sorting network, which achieves depth *O*(log *n*).
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] While this is asymptotically the best known depth for a sorting network, the reliance on expanders makes the constant bound too large for practical use.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Within the AKS sorting network, expander graphs are used to construct bounded depth ε-halvers.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] An ε-halver takes as input a length n permutation of (1, …, *n*) and halves the inputs into two disjoint sets A and B such that for each integer *k* ≤ *n*⁄2 at most εk of the k smallest inputs are in B and at most εk of the k largest inputs are in A.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Following Ajtai, Komlós & Szemerédi (1983), a depth d ε-halver can be constructed as follows.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Take an n vertex, degree d bipartite expander with parts X and Y of equal size such that every subset of vertices of size at most εn has at least ⁠1 – *ε*/*ε*⁠ neighbors.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The vertices of the graph can be thought of as registers that contain inputs and the edges can be thought of as wires that compare the inputs of two registers.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] At the start, arbitrarily place half of the inputs in X and half of the inputs in Y and decompose the edges into d perfect matchings.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] The goal is to end with X roughly containing the smaller half of the inputs and Y containing roughly the larger half of the inputs.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] To achieve this, sequentially process each matching by comparing the registers paired up by the edges of this matching and correct any inputs that are out of order.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Specifically, for each edge of the matching, if the larger input is in the register in X and the smaller input is in the register in Y, then swap the two inputs so that the smaller one is in X and the larger one is in Y.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] It is clear that this process consists of d parallel steps.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] After all d rounds, take A to be the set of inputs in registers in X and B to be the set of inputs in registers in Y to obtain an ε-halving.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] To see this, notice that if a register u in X and v in Y are connected by an edge uv then after the matching with this edge is processed, the input in u is less than that of v.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Furthermore, this property remains true throughout the rest of the process.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Now, suppose for some *k* ≤ *n*⁄2 that more than εk of the inputs (1, …, *k*) are in B.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Then by expansion properties of the graph, the registers of these inputs in Y are connected with at least ⁠1 – *ε*/*ε*⁠*k* registers in X.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] Altogether, this constitutes more than k registers so there must be some register A in X connected to some register B in Y such that the final input of A is not in (1, …, *k*), while the final input of B is.
[src:expander-graphs/expander-graph] This violates the previous property however, and thus the output sets A and B must be an ε-halving.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] In the mathematical field of spectral graph theory, a **Ramanujan graph** is a regular graph whose spectral gap is almost as large as possible (see extremal graph theory).
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Such graphs are excellent spectral expanders.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] As Murty's survey paper notes, Ramanujan graphs "fuse diverse branches of pure mathematics, namely, number theory, representation theory, and algebraic geometry".
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] These graphs are indirectly named after Srinivasa Ramanujan; their name comes from the Ramanujan–Petersson conjecture, which was used in a construction of some of these graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Let G be a connected d -regular graph with n vertices, and let $\lambda _{1}\geq \lambda _{2}\geq \cdots \geq \lambda _{n}$ be the eigenvalues of the adjacency matrix of G (or the spectrum of G ).
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Because G is connected and d -regular, its eigenvalues satisfy $d=\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}$ $\geq \cdots \geq \lambda _{n}\geq -d$ .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] A connected d -regular graph G is a *Ramanujan graph* if $\lambda (G)\leq 2{\sqrt {d-1}}$ .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Many sources uses an alternative definition $\lambda '(G)=\max _{|\lambda _{i}|<d}|\lambda _{i}|$ (whenever there exists $\lambda _{i}$ with $|\lambda _{i}|<d$ ) to define Ramanujan graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] In other words, we allow $-d$ in addition to the "small" eigenvalues.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Since $\lambda _{n}=-d$ if and only if the graph is bipartite, we will refer to the graphs that satisfy this alternative definition but not the first definition as *bipartite Ramanujan graphs*.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] If G is a Ramanujan graph, then $G\times K_{2}$ is a bipartite Ramanujan graph, so the existence of Ramanujan graphs is stronger.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] As observed by Toshikazu Sunada, a regular graph is Ramanujan if and only if its Ihara zeta function satisfies an analog of the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Mathematicians are often interested in constructing infinite families of d -regular Ramanujan graphs for every fixed d .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Such families are useful in applications.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Several explicit constructions of Ramanujan graphs arise as Cayley graphs and are algebraic in nature.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] See Winnie Li's survey on Ramanujan's conjecture and other aspects of number theory relevant to these results.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Lubotzky, Phillips and Sarnak and independently Margulis showed how to construct an infinite family of $(p+1)$ -regular Ramanujan graphs, whenever p is a prime number and $p\equiv 1{\pmod {4}}$ .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Both proofs use the Ramanujan conjecture, which led to the name of Ramanujan graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Besides being Ramanujan graphs, these constructions satisfies some other properties, for example, their girth is $\Omega (\log _{p}(n))$ where n is the number of nodes.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Let us sketch the Lubotzky-Phillips-Sarnak construction.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Let $q\equiv 1{\bmod {4}}$ be a prime not equal to p .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Then $X^{p,q}$ is a $(p+1)$ -regular graph on $n=q(q^{2}-1)$ or $q(q^{2}-1)/2$ vertices depending on whether or not p is a quadratic residue modulo q .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] It is proved that $X^{p,q}$ is a Ramanujan graph.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Morgenstern later extended the construction of Lubotzky, Phillips and Sarnak.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] His extended construction holds whenever p is a prime power.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Arnold Pizer proved that the supersingular isogeny graphs are Ramanujan, although they tend to have lower girth than the graphs of Lubotzky, Phillips, and Sarnak.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Like the graphs of Lubotzky, Phillips, and Sarnak, the degrees of these graphs are always a prime number plus one.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Adam Marcus, Daniel Spielman and Nikhil Srivastava proved the existence of infinitely many d -regular *bipartite* Ramanujan graphs for any $d\geq 3$ .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Later they proved that there exist bipartite Ramanujan graphs of every degree and every number of vertices.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Cohen showed how to construct these graphs in polynomial time.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] The initial work followed an approach of Bilu and Linial.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] They considered an operation called a 2-lift that takes a d -regular graph G with n vertices and a sign on each edge, and produces a new d -regular graph $G'$ on $2n$ vertices.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Bilu & Linial conjectured that there always exists a signing so that every new eigenvalue of $G'$ has magnitude at most $2{\sqrt {d-1}}$ .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] This conjecture guarantees the existence of Ramanujan graphs with degree d and $2^{k}(d+1)$ vertices for any k —simply start with the complete graph $K_{d+1}$ , and iteratively take 2-lifts that retain the Ramanujan property.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Using the method of interlacing polynomials, Marcus, Spielman, and Srivastava proved Bilu & Linial's conjecture holds when G is already a bipartite Ramanujan graph, which is enough to conclude the existence result.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] The sequel proved the stronger statement that a sum of d random bipartite matchings is Ramanujan with non-vanishing probability.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Hall, Puder and Sawin extended the original work of Marcus, Spielman and Srivastava to r-lifts.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] It is still an open problem whether there are infinitely many d -regular (non-bipartite) Ramanujan graphs for any $d\geq 3$ .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] In particular, the problem is open for $d=7$ , the smallest case for which $d-1$ is not a prime power and hence not covered by Morgenstern's construction.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] The constant $2{\sqrt {d-1}}$ in the definition of Ramanujan graphs is asymptotically sharp.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] More precisely, the Alon-Boppana bound states that for every d and $\epsilon >0$ , there exists n such that all d -regular graphs G with at least n vertices satisfy $\lambda (G)>2{\sqrt {d-1}}-\epsilon$ .
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] This means that Ramanujan graphs are essentially the best possible expander graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Therefore, the diameter of Ramanujan graphs are also bounded logarithmically in terms of the number of vertices.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Confirming a conjecture of Alon, Friedman showed that many families of random graphs are *weakly-Ramanujan*.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] This means that for every d and $\epsilon >0$ and for sufficiently large n , a random d -regular n -vertex graph G satisfies $\lambda (G)<2{\sqrt {d-1}}+\epsilon$ with high probability.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] While this result shows that random graphs are close to being Ramanujan, it cannot be used to prove the existence of Ramanujan graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] It is conjectured, though, that random graphs are Ramanujan with substantial probability (roughly 52%).
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] In addition to direct numerical evidence, there is some theoretical support for this conjecture: the spectral gap of a d -regular graph seems to behave according to a Tracy-Widom distribution from random matrix theory, which would predict the same asymptotic.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Expander graphs have many applications to computer science, number theory, and group theory, see e.g Lubotzky's survey on applications to pure and applied math and Hoory, Linial, and Wigderson's survey which focuses on computer science.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Ramanujan graphs are in some sense the best expanders, and so they are especially useful in applications where expanders are needed.
[src:expander-graphs/ramanujan-graph] Importantly, the Lubotzky, Phillips, and Sarnak graphs can be traversed extremely quickly in practice, so they are practical for applications.
[src:expander-graphs/spectral-gap] In mathematics, the **spectral gap** is the difference between the moduli of the two largest eigenvalues of a matrix or operator; alternately, it is sometimes taken as the smallest non-zero eigenvalue.
[src:expander-graphs/spectral-gap] Various theorems relate this difference to other properties of the system.
[src:expander-graphs/spectral-gap] The spectral gap gets its name from the *matrix spectrum*, that is, for a matrix, the list of its eigenvalues.
[src:expander-graphs/spectral-gap] It provides insight on diffusion within the graph: corresponding the spectral gap to the smallest non-zero eigenvalue, it is then the mode of the network state that shows the slowest exponential decay over time.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] In graph theory, the **zig-zag product** of regular graphs $G,H$ , denoted by $G\circ H$ , is a binary operation which takes a large graph ( G ) and a small graph ( H ) and produces a graph that approximately inherits the size of the large one but the degree of the small one.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] An important property of the zig-zag product is that if H is a good expander, then the expansion of the resulting graph is only slightly worse than the expansion of G .
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] Roughly speaking, the zig-zag product $G\circ H$ replaces each vertex of G with a copy (cloud) of H , and connects the vertices by moving a small step (zig) inside a cloud, followed by a big step (zag) between two clouds, and finally performs another small step inside the destination cloud.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] More specifically, the start and endpoints for each edge are at the beginning and end of this "zig-zag-zig" process starting at the points in the replacement product of the two graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] The zigzag product was introduced by Reingold, Vadhan & Wigderson (2000).
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] When the zig-zag product was first introduced, it was used for the explicit construction of constant degree expanders and extractors.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] Later on, the zig-zag product was used in computational complexity theory to prove that symmetric logspace and logspace are equal (Reingold 2008).
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] Let G be a D -regular graph on $[N]$ with rotation map $\mathrm {Rot} _{G}$ and let H be a d -regular graph on $[D]$ with rotation map $\mathrm {Rot} _{H}$ .
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] It is immediate from the definition of the zigzag product that it transforms a graph G to a new graph which is $d^{2}$ -regular.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] Thus if G is a significantly larger than H , the zigzag product will reduce the degree of G .
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] Roughly speaking, by amplifying each vertex of G into a cloud of the size of H the product in fact splits the edges of each original vertex between the vertices of the cloud that replace it.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] The expansion of a graph can be measured by its spectral gap, with an important property of the zigzag product the preservation of the spectral gap.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] That is, if H is a “good enough” expander (has a large spectral gap) then the expansion of the zigzag product is close to the original expansion of G .
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] Formally: Define a $(N,D,\lambda )$ -graph as any D -regular graph on N vertices, whose second largest eigenvalue (of the associated random walk) has absolute value at most $\lambda$ .
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] The zigzag product $G\circ H$ operates separately on each connected component of G .
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] In 2002 Omer Reingold, Salil Vadhan, and Avi Wigderson gave a simple, explicit combinatorial construction of constant-degree expander graphs.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] The construction is iterative, and needs as a basic building block a single, expander of constant size.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] In each iteration the zigzag product is used in order to generate another graph whose size is increased but its degree and expansion remains unchanged.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] This process continues, yielding arbitrarily large expanders.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] In 2005 Omer Reingold introduced an algorithm that solves the undirected st-connectivity problem, the problem of testing whether there is a path between two given vertices in an undirected graph, using only logarithmic space.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] The algorithm relies heavily on the zigzag product.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] Roughly speaking, in order to solve the undirected s-t connectivity problem in logarithmic space, the input graph is transformed, using a combination of powering and the zigzag product, into a constant-degree regular graph with a logarithmic diameter.
[src:expander-graphs/zig-zag-product] The power product increases the expansion (hence reduces the diameter) at the price of increasing the degree, and the zigzag product is used to reduce the degree while preserving the expansion.
